The Translations of Nebrija: Language, Culture, andCirculation in the Early Modern World. BYRON ELLSWORTH HAMANN. 2015. University of Massachusetts Press,Amherst and Boston. xiix + 223 pp. 37illustrations. $22.95 (paperback), ISBN 9781625341709. 
Reviewed by Sergio Romero, University of Texas at Austin 
Thisbookisaninterestingcontributiontocomparativelexicography, modern history, and translation studies.Focusing on the history and impact of Antonio deNebrijasfamousCastilianLatinVocabularioorDictionariumfirstpublishedin1495,theauthorfirsttracesthehistory of its multiple editions until 1610, documentingthemodificationsandadditionsthatNebrijahimselfandothereditorsmadeovertheyears.Next,twofascinatingchapters discuss the use of the Dictionarium as lexical template for the edition of translation dictionaries ofother languages in Europe,theAmericas,andAsia.TheauthordiscussesseveralcasestudiesincludingSpanishEnglish, SpanishFrench, TuscanSpanish, NahuatlSpanish,MixtecSpanish,PurhpechaSpanish,YucatecMayaSpanish,QuechuaSpanish,andTagalogSpanishdictionaries.Mostofthesevolumesincludedalsopartialorfullreversedictionaries.InthesepublicationsNebrijasoriginal lexical entries were often expanded to adapt totherichnessandlexicaldetailofthetargetlanguage.Forexample,Alonso de Molinas NahuatlCastilian vocabulary (1571) duly included Nebrijas original entryRelumbrarorreluzir (toshineortoglitter)butanumber ofvariations were addedtocaptureNahuatl categorizationsofreflectedlight.Forexample,amongseveral,the following subentries translate Nahuatl words referencingspecificqualitiesofreflectedlightassociatedwithparticular objects and situations (pp. 96101): 
Relumbrarelaguaconelsololoscampos.pepe
yoca 
Reluzir las piedras preciosas o los pezes dentro
delaguaconelmovimientoquehazen,oelayun
tamientodelashormigasolaslagunasycampos,
o las gentes ayuntadas por el movimiento quehazen, cuecueyoca. 
Reluzir la seda o la pluma. pepetzca 
Reluzir la grassa de la olla. momotzca. 
The corresponding translations into English are thefollowing: 
To shine, as with the sun on the water or on the
fields To glitter, as with precious stones or fish withinthe water with the movement that they make, orthe anthill, or the lagoons and hills, or peoplejoined by the movement that they make 
To glitter, as with silk or feathers 
To glitter, as with fat in the pot 
The lexicaland structural incommensurabilityof thetwo languages required long descriptions of categoriesthat did not exist in Spanish as with the light reflectionfield above. The author discusses other cases, such asMolinas NahuatlSpanish vocabulario, in which neologisms were created to translate Nahuatl words that didnot have Spanish equivalents. For example, Molina putforthabaxador(onewhobringsthingsdown)totranslateNahuatltlatemohuiani,morphologicallyanagentive nominalizationoftemohuia(bringdown).SuchnominalderivationsfromverbsarenumerousinNahuatlgivenitsrichandregularderivationalmorphology.Incontrast,excessivefidelitytoNebrijasentriessometimesledlexicographers to unfortunate mistranslations or lexicalperiphrasesthatdidnotreflectcommonusageinthetargetlanguage. The introduction of neologisms or semanticshiftsofexistentwordswerealternativestrategies,however, to avoid the undesired connotations of native religiouslexicon.TheMixtectranslationsofferedforentrieslikealtar(altar)inFranciscodeAlvaradosVocabulario enlenguamisteca (1593)wereaCatholicinnovation,asemanticextensionofanextantworddesignedtoseparateChristianaltarfromtheirindigenouscounterparts(p.94).Thus,Hamannopensawindowontothefractious,complex lexical exchange between Spanish and indigenouslanguages ofAsia and theAmericas.That Nebrijas dictionary acted as a lexicographic mediator over such along temporal and geographic space attests to the sociallife of translation dictionaries during the early modernworldandexplainsthesurprisingcorrespondencesamongdictionaries for languages as diverse as Tuscan, Mixtec,and Tagalog. Finally, in Chapter 4 the author discussesthe use of margins to draft manuscript trilingual dictionaries. For example, the margins and blank spaces ofpublished copies ofAlonso de Molinas Nahuatl vocabulario and Maturino Gilbertis Purpecha vocabulariowere annotated with Otomi translations of each entry.Thus, copies of Molinas and Gilbertis bilingual dictionaries turned into the physical medium in which newtrilingual dictionaries were composed.
Hamann adequately discusses the circulation andsocial life of translation dictionaries in early moderntimes. However, some discussion of the circulation ofother types of texts such as doctrines and descriptivegrammars would have helped to contextualize dictionariesasadiscoursegenre.Itisunclearfromtheauthorsdiscussion the extent to which dictionaries modified or 

