Beyond Collapse: Archaeological Perspectives onResilience, Revitalization,and TransformationinComplex Societies. RONALD FAULSEIT, editor. 2016.Southern Illinois University Press, Carbondale. xix +532 pp. 117 figures; 22 tables. $70.00 (paperback),ISBN 9780809333998. 
Reviewed by David Webster, Pennsylvania State University. 
I thought twice before agreeing to review Beyond Collapsebecauseitsmainthemes,resilience,societaltransformation, revitalization, and sustainability, have beenpopular among archaeologists for the last decade. Alltoo often intellectual fashion produces old wine in newbottles.Thereisabitofsuchrepackaginginthisvolume,but overall I found it very engaging and informative.Nineofthe20chaptersaredevotedtoMesoamericaandthe Central Andes, so much will appeal to readers ofLatin American Antiquity. 
ThefirsttwochaptersbyRonaldFaulseitandJosephTainter lay out the rationale for the book: that collapseof complex societies has been overstudied to the greatneglect of processes of persistence and recovery, andbesidescollapsehasbecomeboringandpass.Collapseisunderstoodtobethefragmentationordisarticulationofaparticularpoliticalapparatus(p.5),althoughotherdefinitionsoccurthroughoutthebook.Faulseitbelievescurrentconcernwithresilienceandsustainabilityderivesin part from collective fears that our modern, industrialapparatus is in danger of going off the tracks. His introduction provides a summary of resilience literature andconcepts,whichhavedeeprootsingeneralsystemstheory (an odd omission is the work of David Clarke, whodecades ago introduced many of these ideas to archaeologists of a certain age).Tainters chapter is a fine historical overview of collapse, and it explores a richintellectualtraditioninanuancedandreflectivemanner. 
Centraltoresiliencetheoryisanadaptivecycleusedtodescribe andexplainlongterm cultural processes: 1)colonizationandexploitation,2)conservation,3)release,and 4) reorganization. Some authors heavily integratethese phases into their presentations of archaeologicaldata, while others pay only lip service to them. Thisdidnt disturb me because I always tend to look at thedata and make up my own mind about its larger implications.Thatsaid, Ithink the volume would have benefitedfromafinalsummarychapterthatdiscernedlargerpatterns revealed by the many different culturalsequences presented.
I always respond well to comparative perspectives,and regional coverage is impressive. Old collapse warhorses aretrotted out,includingtheMaya(HogarthandAwe; Hutson et. al; R. Storey), Rome (G. Storey), theAmericanSouthwest(Sedig;Torvinenet.al),Mississippianpolities(EmersonandHedman;Meyers),andtheOlmec(Pool and Loughlin).And kudos to the Mayanist GylesIannone for a very sensible overview of SoutheastAsiaand theKhmer.The casestudiesfallintoseveral scales,some much larger and more complex than others. HanChina (Kidder et. al), Monte Alban (Feinman andNichols),Tula(Andersonetal.),andTiwanaku(Sharratt)were all expansive imperial or statelevel sociopoliticalformations.Others,suchastheMoche(ZoberandSutter)and Nazca (Conlee), were more regional in scope.AlsoincludedaresmallerbutintriguingpolitiesfromtheMississippi Delta (Rodning and Mehta) and the LakeOkeechobee Basin (Thompson). I had no idea of theimpressive architectural remains left behind by theseeffectivelynonagrariangroups.Conspicuouslymissingis SouthwestAsia, whose long Mesopotamian traditionprovides much grist for collapserecovery models.
Lantzas gives a good example of the reconstitutionof viable new social and political formations out of oldfragmentedonesfortheArgolidregionofGreece,arguing convincingly for continuity after the collapse of theBronzeAgepalacecenters.Suchnewformations,however, represent only one dimension of transformation,albeit one consistent with the political recovery centralto the definition of collapse given above. Resilience, atits most basic scale, surely refers to the survival andreproductive success of individuals, regardless of thenewsocial,political,andculturalcircumstancesinwhichthey live. Although there are general qualitative statementsaboutpopulationdynamicsinmanychapters,numericalestimatesofhowmanypeoplewereinvolvedin the precollapse systems and how many descendantsweathered the various transitions are spotty at best(exceptions are the chapters on China, the Olmec,Cahokia, and Tula). A reconstituted system that has 80percent of the precollapse population scale is very different than one that has 20 percent. And surely demographic scale affects the potential for resilience infundamentalways.FiftymillionHanChinesearealwaysgoing to reconstitute some kind of viable descendantsystem,butpolitieswithafewhundredtoafewthousandpeople might not have this capacity.
Readers not familiar with resilience theory will runacross many new terms, some felicitous and some not.Sometimes these are used with no definition, and onehastodigaroundtofindoutwhattheymean(aglossary 

